jason r tibbetts wrote:
&gt;&gt; Sometimes I derive all my test classes from a base test 
&gt;&gt; class that converts the test names from CamelCase to spaces and dumps 
&gt;&gt; them to a file - the &quot;unit documentation&quot;.
&gt;&gt;     
&gt;
&gt; I like this idea. How exactly does the base class implementation work? 
&gt;   
It has custom setup and teardown (I overrode runBare() to call those 
before/after JUnit&#39;s setUp()/tearDown()), and it uses them to open/close 
the unit doc file.
Between the two methods, runBare() also calls a logTest() method that 
writes to the file:

---begin transcript

    private void logTest() {
        unitDoc.println(getTestedClassName() + &quot;:&quot; + this.toString());
    }

    private String getTestedClassName() {
        String testPath = this.getClass().getName();
        String testName = testPath.substring(testPath.lastIndexOf(&#39;.&#39;) + 1);
        return testName.substring(&quot;_Test&quot;.length());
    }

    public String toString() {
        return super.getName().substring(4).replaceAll(&quot;([A-Z])&quot;, &quot; 
$1&quot;).toLowerCase();
    }

---end transcript

You&#39;ll want to tweak this depending on your naming conventions.
